WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:07.280
Oxford Bookworms Library. Stage 1. Shirley Holmes and the Cyber

00:07.280 --> 00:07.600
Thief.

00:07.600 --> 00:14.800
by Jennifer Bassett. Read by Kate Locke. Published and copyright.

00:15.620 --> 00:18.100
Oxford University Press 2013.

00:44.480 --> 00:54.240
Chapter 1. Friday evening. Meeting the client. Friday. It's the

00:54.240 --> 00:56.140
end of the working day.

00:57.140 --> 01:01.640
My friend Layla is in my office drinking coffee. She

01:01.640 --> 01:04.420
tells me a story about one of her clients.

01:05.060 --> 01:11.660
We laugh. Your clients are very difficult people. I say.

01:12.580 --> 01:16.300
Layla is a lawyer. But many of her clients

01:16.300 --> 01:22.600
are very poor people too. She does good work. And

01:22.600 --> 01:27.340
what about you? Says Layla. You're a private

01:27.340 --> 01:34.380
investigator. And your clients are often very difficult and dangerous.

01:35.600 --> 01:40.360
Sahid worries about you. He likes you a lot, you

01:40.360 --> 01:40.580
know.

01:41.860 --> 01:46.900
Sahid is Layla's brother. He's a detective in the police.

01:47.880 --> 01:53.440
Detective Sergeant Sahid Patel. He and Layla are my best

01:53.440 --> 01:53.860
friends.

01:54.940 --> 01:59.080
Sahid worries about me a lot. I smile.

02:00.880 --> 02:06.500
Sahid doesn't need to worry about me. I say. I

02:06.500 --> 02:08.020
can take care of myself.

02:09.560 --> 02:15.540
I finish my coffee and stand up. Friday night. The

02:15.540 --> 02:17.060
best night of the week.

02:17.760 --> 02:21.140
What shall we do this evening? Go to the cinema.

02:22.760 --> 02:30.220
Okay. But let's eat first. I'm really hungry. Layla says.

02:31.100 --> 02:36.420
Oh. And don't forget. Next Friday, you're coming to dinner

02:36.420 --> 02:37.900
at our house.

02:38.800 --> 02:46.700
Sahid's cooking chicken. Great. I say. Sahid's chicken dinner.

02:47.060 --> 02:49.360
Is famous with all his friends.

02:51.180 --> 02:55.340
Layla puts on her coat. And at the door, I

02:55.340 --> 02:56.660
turn off the lights.

02:57.540 --> 03:01.060
I begin to close the door. And the phone rings.

03:01.900 --> 03:06.780
Oh, leave it. Says Layla. It's Friday night.

03:08.580 --> 03:13.480
I go back into the office. I can't do that.

03:14.020 --> 03:14.500
I say.

03:15.160 --> 03:20.600
Perhaps it's a new client. It is. It's a man's

03:20.600 --> 03:22.280
voice speaking quickly.

03:23.220 --> 03:27.620
I listen, say yes and no in the right places

03:27.620 --> 03:29.240
and finish the call.

03:30.620 --> 03:36.920
Sorry Layla. No cinema tonight. Another time, I say.

03:37.620 --> 03:40.500
The client wants me to meet him this evening.

03:41.460 --> 03:46.300
Oh, dear. Layla says. Can't he wait till tomorrow?

03:47.420 --> 03:51.240
He says not. He's a worried man, I think.

03:52.160 --> 03:55.020
We say goodbye and Layla leaves.

03:57.060 --> 04:01.900
The meeting is in a Greek restaurant, not far from

04:01.900 --> 04:02.760
Piccadilly Circus.

04:03.700 --> 04:06.520
I take a bus and then walk.

04:07.400 --> 04:13.240
The Athena restaurant in Old Compton Street is small and

04:13.240 --> 04:13.640
noisy.

04:14.760 --> 04:18.420
The client is sitting at the back at a table

04:18.420 --> 04:20.640
for two, watching the door.

04:21.660 --> 04:24.460
He stands up when I get near the table.

04:25.180 --> 04:31.660
A tall man, nice looking. Brown hair, brown eyes, worried

04:31.660 --> 04:33.840
eyes, tired eyes.

04:34.560 --> 04:36.460
He's not sleeping at night.

04:37.780 --> 04:40.660
Hi, I say. Shirley Holmes.

04:41.660 --> 04:44.120
Jeff Clayton, he says.

04:44.980 --> 04:46.220
Thanks for coming.

04:46.780 --> 04:51.000
We sit down and a waiter brings us bread, olives,

04:51.460 --> 04:55.200
feta cheese, water for me and beer for Jeff Clayton.

04:56.460 --> 04:58.380
Clayton stares at me.

04:59.260 --> 05:04.660
You look very young for a private detective, he says.

05:05.620 --> 05:09.120
How can I help you, Mr. Clayton? I say.

05:09.760 --> 05:13.120
What's your problem? I'm not here to talk about my

05:13.120 --> 05:13.660
age.

05:14.640 --> 05:17.720
Okay, sorry, he says.

05:18.400 --> 05:24.380
I have a business, an electrical design company, Clayton Electric's.

05:24.880 --> 05:25.840
We design.

05:27.140 --> 05:30.860
I take out a piece of paper and push it

05:30.860 --> 05:32.400
across the table to him.

05:33.140 --> 05:35.920
It's the front page from his company's website.

05:36.880 --> 05:39.040
He looks at it, then at me.

05:40.200 --> 05:45.460
Ah, he says, you googled me. You know all about

05:45.460 --> 05:46.080
my company.

05:46.760 --> 05:51.020
No, I say, but I know a little about electrical

05:51.020 --> 05:52.480
design now.

05:53.220 --> 05:57.480
So your problem is a business problem, then.

05:58.600 --> 06:01.840
I eat an olive and a piece of feta cheese.

06:02.700 --> 06:07.280
I love olives and feta, probably because of my Greek

06:07.280 --> 06:07.800
mother.

06:08.880 --> 06:11.820
Jeff Clayton tells me his problem.

06:12.740 --> 06:16.920
His business is losing money because he's not getting new

06:16.920 --> 06:17.300
clients.

06:18.100 --> 06:22.320
Every time he does a quotation for a new job,

06:23.200 --> 06:24.340
he doesn't get it.

06:25.580 --> 06:32.900
In six months, not one new contract, he says, not

06:32.900 --> 06:33.480
one.

06:34.460 --> 06:40.000
My quotations are good. My designs are good. I'm not

06:40.000 --> 06:40.480
expensive.

06:41.720 --> 06:45.960
My prices are good. I have good workers.

06:46.600 --> 06:52.280
Six months ago, I had lots of new business. Everything

06:52.280 --> 06:53.140
was fine.

06:53.960 --> 06:55.600
And now, nothing.

06:56.540 --> 06:57.300
Why?

06:59.180 --> 07:03.740
Who is getting these contracts, then, I ask?

07:04.500 --> 07:06.800
Is it always the same company?

07:07.500 --> 07:09.200
He smiles a little.

07:10.000 --> 07:12.200
Yeah, you got it.

07:12.200 --> 07:18.020
I talk to some people, ask some questions. It's always

07:18.020 --> 07:19.160
the same company.

07:19.980 --> 07:23.440
Spark and flash design in Roehampton.

07:24.120 --> 07:29.760
Their design is nearly the same. Their prices are nearly

07:29.760 --> 07:30.840
the same,

07:31.320 --> 07:36.380
but just a little bit lower. So they get the

07:36.380 --> 07:36.780
contract.

07:38.200 --> 07:44.500
How do you do a quotation? I ask. Tell me.

07:45.900 --> 07:50.060
I look at the client's building with one or two

07:50.060 --> 07:50.960
of my designers.

07:52.160 --> 07:57.420
My design staff then do the plans. It's all done

07:57.420 --> 07:59.020
on computer, of course.

07:59.980 --> 08:03.920
I do the costings for the work and then send

08:03.920 --> 08:06.140
the quotation to the client.

08:06.880 --> 08:11.940
And you keep the quotations on the office computer.

08:12.960 --> 08:18.020
I say, what kind of security do you have?

08:18.920 --> 08:23.020
He tells me the name of the security program on

08:23.020 --> 08:24.160
the office computer.

08:25.000 --> 08:27.540
I know it. It's a good one.

08:28.500 --> 08:32.900
I keep all the quotations and costings in a special

08:32.900 --> 08:35.240
folder on the computer.

08:36.140 --> 08:41.040
He says, nobody can open the folder without the password.

08:42.100 --> 08:46.180
And every file in the folder has a password too.

08:47.480 --> 08:53.780
How many people know the passwords? I ask. Only me.

08:54.760 --> 08:59.360
It sounds all right, but a good hacker can break

08:59.360 --> 09:00.440
through that security.

09:01.080 --> 09:06.700
I think you have a cyber thief on your staff.

09:07.540 --> 09:12.340
I say, someone is getting through your security,

09:12.940 --> 09:18.260
taking the costings information and selling it to this other

09:18.260 --> 09:18.740
company.

09:19.620 --> 09:22.520
Do you trust all your staff?

09:23.500 --> 09:26.480
He looks at me very unhappily.

09:27.440 --> 09:30.480
I did trust them once, he said.

09:31.700 --> 09:32.480
I don't know.

09:33.400 --> 09:37.620
What can I do? There's a very big contract coming

09:37.620 --> 09:38.360
soon.

09:38.960 --> 09:44.520
Blanding's house, near Patney Bridge, all new electrics in the

09:44.520 --> 09:44.900
building.

09:45.760 --> 09:49.000
A Chinese bank is going to open there.

09:49.620 --> 09:53.000
I'm doing the costings for the quotation now.

09:53.840 --> 09:57.000
It must be in by next Friday.

09:57.820 --> 10:02.100
I don't want to lose this one. I can't lose

10:02.100 --> 10:02.920
this one.

10:04.440 --> 10:09.720
He pushes his glass away and looks at me. Can

10:09.720 --> 10:10.920
you help me?

10:12.480 --> 10:14.560
Yes, I think I can.

10:15.340 --> 10:19.240
I eat some more olives and finish the cheese.

10:19.890 --> 10:23.820
I need to be in your office for a day

10:23.820 --> 10:24.340
or two.

10:24.940 --> 10:28.720
Talk to your staff. Is that okay with you?

10:29.460 --> 10:33.420
Sure, he says. Come and go when you like.

10:34.360 --> 10:39.060
I need to do some thinking tomorrow, I say.

10:39.840 --> 10:43.920
Can I phone you on Sunday with my plan, Mr.

10:44.160 --> 10:44.160
Clayton?

10:45.080 --> 10:47.380
Sure, he says again.

10:48.260 --> 10:50.840
But please call me Jeff.

10:51.720 --> 10:53.680
We're working together on this.

10:54.440 --> 10:56.560
Can I call you Shirley?

10:57.540 --> 11:00.860
No, you can't, I say.

11:01.800 --> 11:05.620
In your office, I'm going to be Sally Hawker.

11:06.200 --> 11:08.580
So you call me Sally, right?

11:09.320 --> 11:14.500
And you call me on this mobile number, not the

11:14.500 --> 11:15.680
one on my website.

11:15.680 --> 11:20.540
I give him my business card and show him the

11:20.540 --> 11:22.580
number on the back of the card.

11:23.940 --> 11:27.400
Shirley Holmes, private investigator.

11:28.780 --> 11:32.060
He looks at it, then at the front of the

11:32.060 --> 11:33.560
card and laughs.

11:34.560 --> 11:40.380
Shirley Holmes, that's not your real name, is it?

11:40.890 --> 11:44.780
You changed it because you wanted your name to sound

11:44.780 --> 11:46.620
like Sherlock Holmes.

11:48.070 --> 11:53.360
Maybe, I say, or maybe my mother married a man

11:53.360 --> 11:57.180
called Holmes and they called me Shirley.

12:01.680 --> 12:05.360
Chapter two, Monday in the office.

12:07.340 --> 12:11.980
Early on Sunday evening, I phoned Jeff Clayton on his

12:11.980 --> 12:12.780
home number.

12:13.660 --> 12:15.280
Hi, Mr. Clayton.

12:16.120 --> 12:17.360
Shirley Holmes here.

12:17.900 --> 12:20.780
Can we talk about my plan for tomorrow?

12:21.680 --> 12:23.540
Is this a good time?

12:24.300 --> 12:26.700
Oh, hi Shirley.

12:27.420 --> 12:32.940
I mean, Sally, listen, please call me Jeff.

12:33.760 --> 12:38.280
I don't do this, Mr. Thing, or do you want

12:38.280 --> 12:40.480
me to call you Miss Holmes?

12:41.520 --> 12:45.040
I mean, Miss Hawker, I laugh.

12:46.540 --> 12:48.860
Okay, Jeff.

12:49.780 --> 12:55.060
Now, about tomorrow, I'm going to be a journalist called

12:55.060 --> 12:56.380
Sally Hawker.

12:57.240 --> 13:00.880
And I want to talk to your design staff about

13:00.880 --> 13:01.920
their work.

13:02.940 --> 13:07.000
I'm writing a long piece for Flipside magazine.

13:08.240 --> 13:09.260
Do you know it?

13:10.200 --> 13:11.760
Yes, I do.

13:12.580 --> 13:13.380
It's good.

13:14.780 --> 13:18.340
So, you want me to tell the staff about you

13:18.340 --> 13:19.520
before you arrive?

13:20.440 --> 13:21.520
When are you coming?

13:22.480 --> 13:24.540
About 10 o'clock.

13:25.120 --> 13:26.000
Is that all right?

13:26.940 --> 13:27.500
Fine.

13:28.440 --> 13:31.900
I have files on all my staff here on my

13:31.900 --> 13:32.320
laptop.

13:32.940 --> 13:36.380
Do you want me to email the files to you?

13:37.260 --> 13:39.300
Great, I say.

13:39.900 --> 13:42.220
Please send them right now.

13:44.530 --> 13:48.460
When I arrive at the Clayton Electric's office on Monday

13:48.460 --> 13:49.100
morning,

13:49.960 --> 13:56.300
I know names, addresses, ages, families, schools, universities,

13:57.100 --> 14:00.400
but I need to know much more.

14:01.200 --> 14:02.980
It's a small office.

14:03.760 --> 14:06.620
Everything open, no closed doors.

14:07.400 --> 14:10.060
Faces are friendly, interested.

14:11.460 --> 14:13.980
I'm something new in their working day.

14:15.460 --> 14:18.940
I tell them about me and the IET,

14:19.740 --> 14:23.320
the institution of engineering and technology.

14:24.260 --> 14:29.920
I use my smiley journalist face and my smiley voice.

14:31.080 --> 14:37.000
The IET wants more young people in schools to be

14:37.000 --> 14:38.860
interested in technology.

14:40.060 --> 14:40.760
I tell them.

14:41.220 --> 14:45.860
So they ask me to write something for their Flipside

14:45.860 --> 14:46.460
magazine.

14:48.080 --> 14:52.780
That's the word for 11 to 15 year olds, says

14:52.780 --> 14:53.100
Harry.

14:54.120 --> 14:57.640
I wrote something for them once many years ago.

14:58.600 --> 15:02.460
Harry Bowman, 59 electrical designer,

15:03.000 --> 15:07.240
10 years with Clayton, very good at his job, but

15:07.240 --> 15:08.560
getting old.

15:09.820 --> 15:13.960
So, what do you want to know, asks Anna?

15:14.960 --> 15:19.200
Anna Lund, 29 electrical designer,

15:19.820 --> 15:23.520
two years with Clayton, very clever.

15:25.700 --> 15:30.920
Tell me about your working day, I say, what do

15:30.920 --> 15:33.840
you do, where do you go, who do you talk

15:33.840 --> 15:34.280
to?

15:35.460 --> 15:36.200
Anna laughs.

15:37.460 --> 15:39.460
You must talk to Ken.

15:40.340 --> 15:43.040
He usually goes out with Jeff and talks to the

15:43.040 --> 15:43.320
clients.

15:44.280 --> 15:46.840
Me and Harry just stay here and do the work.

15:48.080 --> 15:49.340
Ken smiles at me.

15:50.520 --> 15:52.540
Don't listen to Anna.

15:53.140 --> 15:57.340
He says, she gets out to see clients too.

15:58.820 --> 16:02.960
Ken Okobi, 32 electrical designer,

16:03.640 --> 16:08.460
five years with Clayton, a good listener, good with the

16:08.460 --> 16:08.860
clients.

16:10.280 --> 16:14.720
There are the three designers and some office staff.

16:15.660 --> 16:17.740
I stay with them all day.

16:18.400 --> 16:21.480
I sit next to the designers at their laptops.

16:22.540 --> 16:26.640
We talk about their computer programs and electrical design.

16:27.780 --> 16:29.280
I laugh when they laugh.

16:30.140 --> 16:33.840
I drink coffee with them, I watch and I listen.

16:35.060 --> 16:37.660
I talk to the office staff too.

16:38.440 --> 16:41.500
Nice people, but they don't know computers.

16:42.460 --> 16:46.680
They can use them, but they don't understand them.

16:47.280 --> 16:50.160
No hackers here, I think.

16:50.160 --> 16:55.200
I go out to lunch with the designers at an

16:55.200 --> 16:56.300
Italian restaurant.

16:57.460 --> 16:59.580
I ask them about money.

17:00.380 --> 17:01.760
Is the pay good?

17:03.040 --> 17:05.760
Very good, Ken says.

17:06.580 --> 17:09.620
Jeff Clayton pays well.

17:10.440 --> 17:12.360
Ah, says Anna.

17:13.160 --> 17:14.840
I'd like more money.

17:15.820 --> 17:19.940
Oh, you always want more, Anna.

17:20.840 --> 17:22.000
Ken says smiling.

17:22.880 --> 17:24.500
And why not?

17:25.160 --> 17:25.780
Says Anna.

17:26.320 --> 17:28.040
I'm good at my job.

17:28.860 --> 17:29.940
She looks at me.

17:30.560 --> 17:33.640
I don't like working for other people.

17:34.100 --> 17:36.660
I want to start my own business.

17:37.600 --> 17:40.900
I want to be a rich woman before I'm 40.

17:41.760 --> 17:43.640
The two men laugh.

17:44.840 --> 17:48.920
When we walk back to the office, I walk with

17:48.920 --> 17:49.220
Harry.

17:50.760 --> 17:53.060
Do you enjoy the work?

17:53.760 --> 17:54.380
I ask.

17:54.980 --> 17:58.000
Yes and no, Harry says.

17:58.780 --> 18:03.000
You see, my wife is not well and I'd like

18:03.000 --> 18:05.840
to be at home to take care of her.

18:06.240 --> 18:09.700
She needs the sun and I'd like to buy a

18:09.700 --> 18:12.240
house in Spain when I start working.

18:13.020 --> 18:15.280
But that's never going to happen.

18:16.720 --> 18:21.440
Ken is walking in front of us and suddenly I

18:21.440 --> 18:22.500
see his shoes.

18:23.500 --> 18:25.340
They look very expensive.

18:26.480 --> 18:29.720
Yes, they're Gucci shoes.

18:30.240 --> 18:31.240
I'm sure of it.

18:32.440 --> 18:36.240
Back in the office, I watch the designers at their

18:36.240 --> 18:37.200
laptops again.

18:38.360 --> 18:40.300
Ken is very helpful.

18:40.300 --> 18:44.500
He tells me a lot about his work and shows

18:44.500 --> 18:46.120
me some of his designs.

18:47.690 --> 18:50.960
Do you take your laptop home at night?

18:51.700 --> 18:52.340
I ask.

18:53.020 --> 18:59.320
Yes, we all do, says Ken, and I always need

18:59.320 --> 19:02.840
my laptop with me when I visit clients.

19:03.400 --> 19:08.800
I work at home in the day, sometimes, says Harry,

19:09.500 --> 19:11.240
because of my wife.

19:12.100 --> 19:14.400
I sometimes need to be at home.

19:15.620 --> 19:16.050
Interesting.

19:17.460 --> 19:23.260
They take their laptop's home, so it's easy for the

19:23.260 --> 19:27.770
hacker to do things at home when nobody is watching.

19:29.330 --> 19:36.390
Five-thirty, going home time, they're closing down laptops, putting

19:36.390 --> 19:37.130
on coats.

19:37.990 --> 19:43.990
The working day is finished, so which one of them

19:43.990 --> 19:46.550
is the hacker and the cyber thief?

19:47.470 --> 19:51.150
It's one of the three designers, I'm sure.

19:52.370 --> 19:53.610
Is it Harry?

19:54.810 --> 19:58.250
He wants a house in Spain for his wife, but

19:58.250 --> 20:00.110
he hasn't got the money for it.

20:01.190 --> 20:07.650
Anna, she's clever, quick, wants to be rich, and she

20:07.650 --> 20:08.930
wants it now.

20:09.710 --> 20:11.650
She doesn't like waiting.

20:13.070 --> 20:14.350
And there's Ken.

20:15.450 --> 20:19.870
He's a nice guy, good at his work, but he's

20:19.870 --> 20:21.530
wearing Gucci shoes.

20:22.930 --> 20:28.250
I get out my laptop, Google Gucci shoes, and look

20:28.250 --> 20:29.130
for the prices.

20:31.550 --> 20:34.350
£470 for a pair of shoes.

20:35.570 --> 20:38.950
Where does Ken get that kind of money?

20:39.750 --> 20:45.370
I need to know more about Ken's home life, but

20:45.370 --> 20:49.270
first, I need to visit the Weasel.

20:51.630 --> 20:56.230
I don't know the Weasel's real name, nobody knows it.

20:56.810 --> 21:00.930
He lives in a great big apartment in Bayeswater.

21:01.810 --> 21:05.390
It's really just one big room with computers.

21:05.390 --> 21:11.630
Computers, big and small computers, everywhere.

21:13.090 --> 21:18.210
The Weasel is probably the best hacker in England, maybe

21:18.210 --> 21:19.050
in Europe.

21:20.550 --> 21:24.630
I sit on one of the Weasel's black chairs, drink

21:24.630 --> 21:25.410
black coffee,

21:26.030 --> 21:28.970
and look around the great dark room.

21:29.830 --> 21:33.310
The only light is from computer screens.

21:34.330 --> 21:38.970
Indian music is playing quietly, from one of the computers.

21:40.990 --> 21:44.990
Don't you ever go out, I say?

21:45.870 --> 21:51.330
See some daylight, look at some trees, feel the sun

21:51.330 --> 21:52.250
on your face.

21:53.730 --> 21:56.430
Where do I want to see daylight?

21:57.550 --> 21:58.130
Our trees.

21:59.190 --> 22:02.850
The Weasel says, he looks around at his computers.

22:04.030 --> 22:07.850
All the world comes to me here. I don't need

22:07.850 --> 22:08.390
daylight.

22:09.810 --> 22:10.950
He looks at me.

22:12.090 --> 22:14.090
And what do you need, Hawker?

22:14.610 --> 22:19.070
He always calls me Hawker. He likes that name better

22:19.070 --> 22:19.770
than Holmes.

22:20.670 --> 22:22.970
You always need something.

22:24.490 --> 22:27.990
Years ago, the Weasel went through a bad time.

22:28.710 --> 22:32.670
I helped him then, and he doesn't forget that.

22:33.310 --> 22:35.870
I can ask him for help when I want.

22:37.150 --> 22:40.190
I tell him about Jeff Clayton's problem.

22:41.750 --> 22:46.310
I want to watch three laptops, probably through the night.

22:47.250 --> 22:50.130
I need to catch the person when they get through

22:50.130 --> 22:52.750
the security on the main office computer.

22:53.810 --> 22:55.510
How many passwords?

22:56.990 --> 22:57.730
The Weasel asks.

22:57.730 --> 22:58.930
Two.

23:00.270 --> 23:05.630
One for the quotations folder, and then every file has

23:05.630 --> 23:07.110
its password too.

23:07.910 --> 23:12.850
Mmm, that's a clever Hawker, says the Weasel.

23:13.670 --> 23:17.530
Okay, you need a Trojan horse program.

23:18.430 --> 23:22.630
I can write that for you. Give me 24 hours.

23:26.490 --> 23:30.970
Chapter 3, Tuesday, on the streets.

23:33.510 --> 23:37.690
I meet Jeff in Richmond Park at 6.30 on

23:37.690 --> 23:38.710
Tuesday morning.

23:39.650 --> 23:43.370
A park is a good place to meet, away from

23:43.370 --> 23:45.410
watching eyes and listening ears.

23:46.110 --> 23:48.790
We walk up Sawyer's Hill.

23:49.510 --> 23:52.610
It's beautiful in the park in the area.

23:52.610 --> 23:56.330
Early morning, there's not many people at that time.

23:57.010 --> 24:01.330
Maybe a walker with a dog, or somebody running.

24:02.270 --> 24:06.330
It's quiet and green, with lots of big trees.

24:07.370 --> 24:08.570
I love trees.

24:10.710 --> 24:14.730
Jeff Clayton is not interested in trees.

24:15.950 --> 24:20.670
Who is it? He says, who's my cyber thief?

24:20.670 --> 24:21.890
Do you know yet?

24:22.530 --> 24:24.670
No, I say.

24:25.270 --> 24:27.990
I tell him about my day in his office.

24:28.990 --> 24:32.210
It's one of your three designers.

24:32.830 --> 24:36.490
I'm sure of it, but we need to catch them

24:36.490 --> 24:38.090
when they're doing it.

24:39.090 --> 24:41.310
But how, says Jeff?

24:42.550 --> 24:46.550
I'm going to put a Trojan on your office computer.

24:47.430 --> 24:53.130
When the designers turn on their laptops, the Trojan downloads.

24:54.210 --> 24:58.910
I can then watch everything on their laptops, on my

24:58.910 --> 24:59.270
laptop.

25:00.390 --> 25:03.390
But they know nothing about it.

25:04.250 --> 25:08.370
I can see them, but they can't see me.

25:09.490 --> 25:15.430
A Trojan, says Jeff, but they're dangerous.

25:16.530 --> 25:17.930
Are you sure about this?

25:18.730 --> 25:21.830
Where does this Trojan come from?

25:22.430 --> 25:23.490
How do you get it?

25:24.690 --> 25:27.070
A friend is writing it for me.

25:27.770 --> 25:31.110
I say, what friend, who?

25:32.290 --> 25:36.250
Sorry, I can't tell you that, I say.

25:37.050 --> 25:40.870
Look, do you want to catch this thief or not?

25:41.570 --> 25:44.870
Trust me, we need to do this.

25:45.830 --> 25:50.650
Then, when the Trojan is in place, you upload your

25:50.650 --> 25:52.650
costings for the new quotation.

25:53.850 --> 25:54.430
What was it?

25:55.250 --> 25:56.530
Blandings, something?

25:57.950 --> 26:02.450
Blandings House, a Chinese bank is moving into the building.

26:03.310 --> 26:05.370
They want everything new.

26:06.830 --> 26:09.690
Which Chinese bank is that?

26:10.490 --> 26:17.190
I ask, oh, I can't tell you that, Jeff says,

26:17.950 --> 26:18.690
and looks at me.

26:19.710 --> 26:24.110
I laugh, and after a minute, he laughs too.

26:24.910 --> 26:30.290
And then, we wait and watch, I say.

26:31.750 --> 26:36.230
I use my motorbike when I want to move around

26:36.230 --> 26:37.170
London a lot.

26:38.150 --> 26:42.830
I look like a motorbike messenger taking letters and packets

26:42.830 --> 26:44.230
from A to B.

26:45.290 --> 26:50.030
The letters and packets never arrive, of course, but nobody

26:50.030 --> 26:50.970
knows that.

26:51.730 --> 26:55.570
They just see a person all in black on a

26:55.570 --> 26:59.330
motorbike and think, oh, a messenger.

27:00.630 --> 27:07.710
Nobody sees your face, nobody knows your name, nobody remembers

27:07.710 --> 27:08.190
you.

27:09.070 --> 27:09.990
This is good.

27:11.410 --> 27:16.090
Harry, Ken, and Anna are at work in the Clayton

27:16.090 --> 27:17.190
Electric's office,

27:17.910 --> 27:20.670
so I'm going to look at their homes.

27:21.830 --> 27:25.810
Sometimes you learn things from a person's home.

27:26.950 --> 27:31.390
Harry Bowman lives in a little house in a quiet

27:31.390 --> 27:33.710
street near a queue gardens.

27:34.610 --> 27:39.790
It's a nice house with a nice little garden in

27:39.790 --> 27:40.690
a nice street.

27:41.550 --> 27:45.370
Lots of nice people in nice little houses.

27:46.530 --> 27:50.090
I ride up and down the street once or twice,

27:50.610 --> 27:52.850
but it tells me nothing.

27:54.810 --> 27:56.910
It's the same for Anna Lund.

27:57.810 --> 28:02.150
She lives in an apartment in a house in Barnes.

28:03.330 --> 28:08.510
There are four apartments in the house, but nobody is

28:08.510 --> 28:09.050
at home,

28:09.990 --> 28:12.590
so I can't ask any questions.

28:14.050 --> 28:17.670
I walk around the back of the house, but there

28:17.670 --> 28:19.010
is nothing to see.

28:20.370 --> 28:28.410
Ken Okobi lives on Richmond Hill, big houses, big expensive

28:28.410 --> 28:32.510
houses looking down over the river Thames.

28:34.030 --> 28:38.310
I stop the bike by his house and get out

28:38.310 --> 28:39.090
my iPad.

28:40.230 --> 28:43.530
I'm just a messenger checking an address.

28:43.530 --> 28:49.150
A car arrives and stops outside the house.

28:50.310 --> 28:54.350
An older man gets out and goes into the house,

28:55.230 --> 28:56.470
Ken's father.

28:57.990 --> 29:01.790
The car is dark blue, long and low.

29:02.890 --> 29:09.810
It's a Porsche, only very, very rich people drive a

29:09.810 --> 29:10.150
Porsche.

29:11.230 --> 29:16.690
There are two small boys walking down the street, carrying

29:16.690 --> 29:17.120
skateboards.

29:18.430 --> 29:22.710
They stop next to me and stare at my motorbike.

29:24.150 --> 29:26.130
Is that a Yamaha?

29:27.150 --> 29:32.210
One of them says, yes, I say, do you like

29:32.210 --> 29:32.570
it?

29:33.090 --> 29:35.470
Yeah, it's cool.

29:36.470 --> 29:40.130
The boy says, what do you think?

29:40.130 --> 29:44.590
Think of that car, I say, looking at the Porsche.

29:45.550 --> 29:50.070
I'd like one of those, that's a really cool car.

29:51.590 --> 29:56.410
That's Mr Okobi's Porsche, the other boy says.

29:57.270 --> 30:02.330
He lives in this house here, my dad knows him.

30:03.490 --> 30:07.670
He's got lots of money then, I say.

30:08.460 --> 30:13.290
He's an oil millionaire from Nigeria, my dad says.

30:14.030 --> 30:17.030
He's got three cars, not four.

30:18.090 --> 30:18.890
Says the boy.

30:20.380 --> 30:25.250
So, Ken wears Gucci shoes because he has a rich

30:25.250 --> 30:25.810
daddy.

30:26.670 --> 30:31.710
Not because he's a thief, an interesting person.

30:32.470 --> 30:36.270
He doesn't need to work with a rich family like

30:36.270 --> 30:36.670
that.

30:37.310 --> 30:40.170
But he does, I like that.

30:41.870 --> 30:45.570
The boys move on and I check my iPad for

30:45.570 --> 30:45.890
messages.

30:47.170 --> 30:52.390
There's a green light on the screen, two emails, one

30:52.390 --> 30:55.430
from Leila, one from the Weasel.

30:56.530 --> 31:01.130
The Weasel's email has no message, just a file attachment,

31:02.090 --> 31:03.450
a file called

31:05.770 --> 31:11.270
gardenforflowers.exe, it's the Trojan Horse Program.

31:13.720 --> 31:17.730
At 10 o'clock that evening, Jeff Clayton and I

31:17.730 --> 31:19.590
meet outside his office.

31:20.490 --> 31:25.130
Jeff opens the doors, puts the lights on, makes us

31:25.130 --> 31:26.050
a cup of coffee.

31:27.050 --> 31:30.890
I sit down at the main computer and get out

31:30.890 --> 31:31.970
a memory stick.

31:33.930 --> 31:37.610
What's on that stick? asks Jeff.

31:38.750 --> 31:43.450
The Trojan, my friend emailed it to me and I

31:43.450 --> 31:45.010
copied it onto this stick.

31:45.870 --> 31:49.990
I put the stick into the computer and start to

31:49.990 --> 31:51.910
upload the Trojan file.

31:53.250 --> 31:56.230
Jeff watches, he's very worried.

31:57.110 --> 31:59.210
Are you sure about this?

32:00.110 --> 32:04.030
He says, Trojans can do very bad things.

32:05.230 --> 32:10.610
Yes, they can, I say, but I'm not doing bad

32:10.610 --> 32:11.090
things.

32:11.670 --> 32:16.010
I'm just going to watch and catch your cyber thief,

32:16.250 --> 32:16.790
we hope.

32:17.930 --> 32:21.550
Is your Blanding's house quotation ready yet?

32:22.510 --> 32:24.770
Nearly, says Jeff.

32:25.470 --> 32:27.690
I'm going to finish the last bits tonight.

32:29.130 --> 32:35.530
Okay, tomorrow morning upload the Blanding's file into the quotations

32:35.530 --> 32:37.270
folder on the office

32:37.270 --> 32:42.150
computer in the usual way and then tell the staff

32:42.150 --> 32:44.950
about it, but just quietly.

32:45.910 --> 32:52.250
It's just another quotation, don't do or say anything different,

32:52.910 --> 32:54.210
just be normal.

32:55.790 --> 32:58.390
I stand up and put my coat on.

32:59.530 --> 33:04.150
Nothing's going to happen before tomorrow night when they take

33:04.150 --> 33:05.410
their laptops home.

33:06.750 --> 33:13.150
Then you're on the night watch, Jeff says, and what

33:13.150 --> 33:13.950
do I do?

33:14.770 --> 33:20.450
Nothing, I say, stay at home, wait for my call.

33:24.830 --> 33:29.670
Chapter four, Wednesday, watching in the night.

33:31.810 --> 33:35.390
When I'm working on a case, I like to check

33:35.390 --> 33:35.990
everything.

33:37.150 --> 33:40.710
Perhaps this isn't the first time for our cyber thief.

33:41.510 --> 33:45.990
Cyber crime gets bigger and bigger every year.

33:46.750 --> 33:50.350
Lots of people are doing it again and again.

33:51.230 --> 33:56.890
Every private investigator needs to have a good friend in

33:56.890 --> 33:57.510
the police.

33:58.750 --> 34:00.410
iPhone, Saheed.

34:01.930 --> 34:04.690
Saheed, dear Saheed!

34:05.630 --> 34:09.250
I say, I need your help again.

34:10.710 --> 34:14.670
Why are you only nice to me when you want

34:14.670 --> 34:15.390
something?

34:16.330 --> 34:20.990
Saheed says, he's smiling, I can hear it in his

34:20.990 --> 34:21.390
voice.

34:23.230 --> 34:25.810
I'm always nice to you.

34:26.610 --> 34:30.530
I say, and you're going to be nice to me

34:30.530 --> 34:30.910
today.

34:31.770 --> 34:36.190
I know it's, I have some names for you.

34:36.630 --> 34:40.230
Do any of these people have a police record?

34:41.150 --> 34:43.150
It's so easy for you.

34:43.790 --> 34:46.610
You just have to put the names into the police

34:46.610 --> 34:48.730
computer and...

34:48.730 --> 34:53.050
Okay, okay, says Saheed.

34:53.770 --> 34:58.390
I have a meeting very soon, but I can give

34:58.390 --> 35:02.790
you 10 minutes now, not a second more.

35:03.470 --> 35:04.910
Give me the names.

35:05.970 --> 35:11.390
I give him Ken, Anna, and Harry, and then 15

35:11.390 --> 35:13.950
names from the Spark and Flash website.

35:15.050 --> 35:19.850
All these people work for a company called Spark and

35:19.850 --> 35:22.370
Flash Design, I say.

35:23.390 --> 35:26.090
Spark and Flash Design!

35:26.830 --> 35:31.190
Saheed says, he's typing the names on his keyboard.

35:31.990 --> 35:34.290
I can hear it through the phone.

35:34.910 --> 35:36.530
Clack, clack, clack.

35:37.930 --> 35:41.070
What kind of company is that?

35:42.670 --> 35:46.910
It's an electrical design company, I say.

35:47.890 --> 35:52.650
Saheed laughs, what a stupid name.

35:53.550 --> 35:58.770
He says, who wants Spark and Flash and their electrics?

35:59.730 --> 36:06.310
Well, of course not, I say, but people laugh and

36:06.310 --> 36:10.770
then they remember the name and that's clever.

36:12.590 --> 36:15.630
Here we are, says Saheed.

36:16.370 --> 36:18.830
He reads from his computer screen.

36:20.390 --> 36:25.130
Ken Okobi, nothing, Anna Lund, nothing.

36:26.210 --> 36:30.710
No, there's nothing in the records for any of those

36:30.710 --> 36:31.130
names.

36:31.870 --> 36:33.110
Is that helpful?

36:34.330 --> 36:38.110
Yes, and no, I say.

36:38.910 --> 36:40.950
But it was a great help to me.

36:41.850 --> 36:43.470
Thanks a million, Saheed.

36:44.450 --> 36:47.350
No problem, Saheed says.

36:48.470 --> 36:50.990
See you Friday night then.

36:53.070 --> 36:56.710
I have a quiet day, I go for a walk,

36:57.210 --> 37:00.430
do some shopping, have a quick lunch with Leyla.

37:01.490 --> 37:02.850
How's it going?

37:03.550 --> 37:07.710
She asks, the new case, the man in the Greek

37:07.710 --> 37:08.550
restaurant?

37:09.790 --> 37:15.550
Ok, I say, I never talk about my cases with

37:15.550 --> 37:16.250
my friends.

37:17.050 --> 37:20.250
Only Saheed, because he's a detective.

37:20.750 --> 37:22.730
And he understands the work.

37:23.690 --> 37:29.350
Jeff's staff usually finish work about 5.30, Jeff told

37:29.350 --> 37:29.650
me.

37:30.330 --> 37:34.290
They get home by about 6.30 maybe.

37:35.470 --> 37:39.550
At 5 o'clock, I'm at home, my laptop is

37:39.550 --> 37:43.590
ready and I have three little windows on the screen.

37:44.490 --> 37:49.130
One for Ken's laptop, one for Anna's and one for

37:49.130 --> 37:49.810
Harry's.

37:50.830 --> 37:53.070
I'm good at waiting and watching.

37:53.670 --> 37:57.890
Every private investigator needs to be good at these things.

37:58.970 --> 38:03.890
You learn to watch every little thing and remember it.

38:04.470 --> 38:07.910
You learn to go for a long time without sleep

38:07.910 --> 38:12.070
and then sleep for 12 or 14 hours.

38:13.990 --> 38:18.590
8 o'clock, I drink coffee and read on my

38:18.590 --> 38:18.970
iPad.

38:19.830 --> 38:23.890
I find a story on the internet about cybercrime.

38:24.750 --> 38:26.550
It's not very good.

38:27.410 --> 38:30.890
A hacker in a high school is taking millions of

38:30.890 --> 38:32.750
dollars from a bank in Switzerland.

38:33.790 --> 38:35.550
It sounds so easy.

38:36.770 --> 38:39.590
But in real life, it isn't easy.

38:40.710 --> 38:44.570
A really clever hacker can get through a bank security

38:44.570 --> 38:47.610
but it's very difficult.

38:48.970 --> 38:53.010
The weasel can do it, I think, but he doesn't.

38:53.550 --> 38:57.870
Well, I don't know. I don't ask questions.

38:59.390 --> 39:04.810
11 o'clock, I make some more coffee and drink

39:04.810 --> 39:05.450
it black.

39:07.030 --> 39:09.670
My laptop screen shows nothing.

39:10.610 --> 39:14.570
Maybe the cyber thief is waiting for a quiet time

39:14.570 --> 39:15.530
late at night.

39:15.530 --> 39:21.830
One o'clock, my iPad suddenly shows a green light.

39:22.630 --> 39:24.910
It's a message from the weasel.

39:26.650 --> 39:29.050
How's it going? He writes.

39:30.750 --> 39:34.010
Nothing happening yet. I write back.

39:35.630 --> 39:38.690
Are the garden flowers all right?

39:39.890 --> 39:42.430
Yes, they're beautiful.

39:43.210 --> 39:45.370
Thank you very much.

39:46.810 --> 39:48.310
No problem.

39:49.870 --> 39:52.630
Are you doing the night watch then?

39:54.210 --> 39:58.330
Yes, boring. What are you doing?

39:59.270 --> 40:04.150
Talking to a guy in California about the new internet

40:04.150 --> 40:05.410
laws in America.

40:07.050 --> 40:08.610
Bad news, eh?

40:09.570 --> 40:13.250
Very bad. We don't want these laws.

40:14.290 --> 40:17.730
The internet must be free for everyone.

40:19.070 --> 40:21.470
I look at my laptop screen.

40:22.250 --> 40:24.850
Hey, something's happening.

40:25.350 --> 40:27.810
Must go. Talk to you later.

40:29.210 --> 40:32.610
I close my iPad and turn to my laptop.

40:32.610 --> 40:38.510
The screen is flashing. Somebody is getting into the Clayton

40:38.510 --> 40:39.630
office computer.

40:40.870 --> 40:44.210
They get to the password for the quotations folder.

40:45.690 --> 40:48.830
Yes, they break through that.

40:49.330 --> 40:52.530
Now the password for the blending file.

40:54.010 --> 40:55.830
And they're through that.

40:56.610 --> 41:01.010
Now the file is downloading to a laptop.

41:02.610 --> 41:04.230
Anna's laptop.

41:08.650 --> 41:09.950
Chapter five.

41:10.770 --> 41:13.110
Thursday. Taking photos.

41:15.470 --> 41:16.530
I phone Jeff.

41:17.530 --> 41:20.130
Hey, Jeff. Are you asleep?

41:21.590 --> 41:23.750
I'm not now. He says.

41:24.550 --> 41:25.470
What's happening?

41:26.550 --> 41:29.490
I have a name for you. Are you ready?

41:30.290 --> 41:31.090
Yes.

41:32.230 --> 41:33.270
Anna Lund.

41:34.610 --> 41:37.490
He doesn't say anything for a minute then.

41:38.450 --> 41:41.370
Anna. It's Anna.

41:42.370 --> 41:43.590
Are you sure?

41:44.750 --> 41:46.110
It's Anna's laptop.

41:47.210 --> 41:50.970
Perhaps she did it or perhaps a spark and flash

41:50.970 --> 41:51.870
friend did it,

41:52.190 --> 41:54.210
but it's her laptop.

41:55.870 --> 41:56.330
Right.

41:57.290 --> 41:59.930
Jeff Clayton's voice is angry.

42:00.910 --> 42:03.050
I'm calling the police in the morning.

42:03.850 --> 42:06.910
They can come to the office and when Anna walks

42:06.910 --> 42:07.450
in,

42:07.750 --> 42:08.450
wait!

42:09.330 --> 42:09.890
I say.

42:10.630 --> 42:12.370
Here's the bad news.

42:13.450 --> 42:17.970
Anna or her friend downloaded the Blandings file,

42:18.590 --> 42:22.050
but they didn't keep the file on her laptop.

42:22.890 --> 42:25.650
It went onto a memory stick.

42:26.870 --> 42:30.510
I took some screenshots of the file download.

42:31.530 --> 42:33.130
We can show the police those,

42:33.850 --> 42:36.930
but they don't prove anything.

42:38.350 --> 42:41.410
Somebody took the file from the office computer.

42:42.210 --> 42:46.730
Yes, but the files not on her laptop now.

42:47.690 --> 42:51.050
But the download happened on her laptop.

42:51.770 --> 42:55.170
Says Jeff. Of course she's the thief.

42:56.330 --> 42:57.490
Listen, Jeff.

42:58.150 --> 42:59.870
What's she going to say?

43:00.710 --> 43:01.630
She's going to say,

43:02.070 --> 43:02.950
what file?

43:03.610 --> 43:04.930
What are you talking about?

43:05.330 --> 43:07.810
Where is this file on my laptop?

43:08.690 --> 43:11.110
I don't know anything about a file.

43:11.850 --> 43:16.030
She's not stupid and she's going to be ready for

43:16.030 --> 43:16.910
any question.

43:17.850 --> 43:18.550
She did it.

43:18.950 --> 43:22.510
Yes, but we can't prove it.

43:23.650 --> 43:24.410
Yes.

43:24.410 --> 43:27.070
Yes, I see.

43:28.370 --> 43:30.050
You're right, Shirley.

43:31.210 --> 43:33.350
Jeff's voice is very unhappy.

43:34.510 --> 43:37.390
So, what are we going to do?

43:38.390 --> 43:42.430
Well, the Trojan horse was Plan A,

43:43.070 --> 43:46.050
and now I have Plan B, I say.

43:46.950 --> 43:49.810
Where is the Blandings file now?

43:50.670 --> 43:51.890
We need to know that.

43:52.610 --> 43:56.650
Maybe Spark and Flash have got the file already,

43:57.610 --> 43:59.870
but maybe they haven't,

44:00.070 --> 44:04.330
and maybe Anna is meeting somebody tomorrow.

44:05.090 --> 44:09.310
So I'm going to watch Anna all day.

44:10.330 --> 44:11.510
Where does she go?

44:12.390 --> 44:13.270
Who does she meet?

44:15.130 --> 44:15.610
Okay.

44:16.470 --> 44:17.930
What can I do?

44:18.890 --> 44:19.670
asks Jeff.

44:21.170 --> 44:23.170
Go into the office tomorrow.

44:24.250 --> 44:24.590
Be normal.

44:25.290 --> 44:26.110
Be nice to Anna.

44:26.690 --> 44:28.070
Nice to everyone.

44:28.810 --> 44:32.430
Talk about work, the weather, the football, whatever.

44:33.250 --> 44:35.430
We know about Anna,

44:35.890 --> 44:37.810
but she doesn't know that.

44:38.370 --> 44:40.410
We don't want her to worry.

44:41.730 --> 44:44.050
Okay, I get it.

44:44.730 --> 44:45.270
Jeff says,

44:45.950 --> 44:47.450
watch and listen.

44:48.010 --> 44:50.910
Text me when Anna does anything.

44:51.510 --> 44:54.210
When she leaves the office, goes to lunch,

44:54.870 --> 44:56.110
makes a phone call.

44:56.950 --> 45:00.490
Use my Sally Hawker mobile number.

45:02.770 --> 45:05.650
I sleep for three or four hours,

45:06.210 --> 45:08.430
then get up, drink more coffee,

45:09.110 --> 45:10.170
and call a taxi.

45:11.010 --> 45:13.890
I want to be outside Anna's apartment

45:14.530 --> 45:16.850
before the buses start in the morning.

45:18.250 --> 45:20.350
I wear my student disguise.

45:21.590 --> 45:23.410
I have long hair, a big hat,

45:23.890 --> 45:25.810
and a wonderful long skirt

45:25.810 --> 45:28.770
with red and yellow flowers all over it.

45:29.350 --> 45:30.710
It's a great skirt.

45:31.670 --> 45:35.470
People look at a skirt and not at the face.

45:37.510 --> 45:40.710
Anna leaves her apartment at eight o'clock,

45:41.370 --> 45:43.650
walks down the street to the bus stop.

45:43.890 --> 45:46.210
And gets on the first bus.

45:47.130 --> 45:49.370
There are lots of people on the bus.

45:50.150 --> 45:54.750
Anna goes upstairs and I sit downstairs.

45:56.050 --> 45:59.350
She gets off the bus and walks to the office.

46:00.450 --> 46:03.370
And I'm 20 meters behind her.

46:04.250 --> 46:05.770
She doesn't meet anybody.

46:06.450 --> 46:08.610
She doesn't talk to anybody.

46:09.870 --> 46:10.910
I text Jeff.

46:12.390 --> 46:16.450
Anna arriving now, nothing happened.

46:17.770 --> 46:19.970
A text comes back from Jeff.

46:20.990 --> 46:21.690
Okay.

46:23.290 --> 46:26.970
I find a sandwich bar not far from the Clayton

46:26.970 --> 46:27.290
office.

46:28.370 --> 46:31.230
I sit by the window and from there

46:31.230 --> 46:34.290
I can see the door of the Clayton office.

46:35.610 --> 46:36.570
I'm hungry.

46:37.250 --> 46:40.170
I eat two chicken and tomato sandwiches

46:40.170 --> 46:44.130
on brown bread and drink two cups of tea.

46:45.190 --> 46:48.370
I read on my iPad, watch the clock,

46:49.130 --> 46:52.230
and when the waiter gives me a hard look,

46:53.150 --> 46:55.110
I buy another cup of tea.

46:56.430 --> 46:58.490
Seven cups of tea.

46:59.570 --> 47:01.470
It's a long morning.

47:02.970 --> 47:05.690
A text arrives on my phone.

47:06.930 --> 47:09.490
Anna leaving for lunch now.

47:10.030 --> 47:11.070
Everything normal.

47:11.750 --> 47:14.330
We talked about last night's football.

47:15.790 --> 47:19.470
When Anna comes out, I'm standing in the street

47:19.730 --> 47:21.970
looking into a shop window.

47:22.910 --> 47:25.110
She walks quickly for 10 minutes

47:25.430 --> 47:29.150
and then goes into a big pub by the river.

47:29.890 --> 47:34.850
It's lunchtime and the pub is noisy, full of people.

47:35.730 --> 47:39.990
I go in at another door and look around for

47:39.990 --> 47:40.230
Anna.

47:41.270 --> 47:45.410
She's with a man, a tall man with red hair.

47:46.370 --> 47:48.170
Is he just a friend or?

47:49.470 --> 47:52.230
No, he's more than a friend.

47:53.070 --> 47:54.570
Anna is kissing him.

47:55.350 --> 47:56.690
He's kissing her back.

47:57.670 --> 47:59.470
He has his arm around her.

48:00.330 --> 48:03.930
They're excited, happy, laughing,

48:04.850 --> 48:07.830
I move a little nearer to them.

48:08.730 --> 48:11.590
I get my phone out, hold the phone to my

48:11.590 --> 48:11.910
ear,

48:12.530 --> 48:15.270
but take photos, lots of them.

48:15.990 --> 48:17.430
Nobody looks at me.

48:18.110 --> 48:21.430
I'm just a student in a long flowery skirt

48:22.030 --> 48:24.110
talking on my mobile phone.

48:25.490 --> 48:27.830
I take a taxi back to my office

48:28.310 --> 48:30.370
and sit down at my big laptop.

48:31.490 --> 48:33.710
I download the photos to the laptop.

48:34.850 --> 48:37.170
The camera in my phone is a good one

48:37.690 --> 48:40.370
and these photos are really good.

48:41.350 --> 48:44.410
So, who is this guy with Anna?

48:46.510 --> 48:50.270
15 people work for Spark and Flash Design

48:50.950 --> 48:53.170
and I have all the names.

48:54.450 --> 48:56.590
I begin with the people at the top of the

48:56.590 --> 48:57.030
company,

48:57.810 --> 49:01.470
put their names into Google and hit search.

49:02.270 --> 49:04.870
I'm looking for photographs.

49:06.410 --> 49:06.950
Yes!

49:07.770 --> 49:08.830
Got him.

49:09.770 --> 49:13.030
The third name brings up lots of photographs

49:13.310 --> 49:16.490
of a tall man with red hair.

49:17.730 --> 49:21.630
He has a Facebook page with all his photos on

49:21.630 --> 49:21.770
it.

49:22.430 --> 49:23.770
Stupid man.

49:25.090 --> 49:27.610
Steven Nyberg, director,

49:28.650 --> 49:30.190
Spark and Flash Design.

49:32.510 --> 49:36.110
I meet Jeff Clayton in Richmond Park again.

49:36.870 --> 49:38.630
This time, it's raining,

49:39.210 --> 49:42.350
so we sit in his car and make a plan.

49:43.190 --> 49:44.570
Plan C.

49:48.810 --> 49:52.650
Chapter 6, Friday, the end of the road.

49:54.630 --> 49:57.850
Early Friday morning, I'm in the sandwich bar

49:57.850 --> 49:59.090
near the Clayton office,

49:59.090 --> 50:01.590
waiting for a text from Jeff.

50:02.650 --> 50:06.090
I'm early, so I have a chicken and tomato sandwich

50:06.090 --> 50:06.650
again.

50:07.610 --> 50:08.610
They're good sandwiches.

50:09.890 --> 50:11.550
A text arrives from Jeff.

50:12.490 --> 50:13.350
She's here.

50:13.950 --> 50:14.810
Come in now.

50:15.930 --> 50:18.430
Today, I'm Shirley Holmes,

50:18.910 --> 50:19.870
private investigator.

50:20.910 --> 50:22.890
Quiet dark clothes.

50:24.010 --> 50:25.290
No flowery skirts,

50:26.010 --> 50:28.130
no journalist smiley face.

50:29.090 --> 50:31.150
I walk through the Clayton office

50:31.150 --> 50:33.430
to Jeff's little room at the back.

50:34.290 --> 50:36.650
Ken and Harry stare at me.

50:37.550 --> 50:40.490
Do they see Sally Hawker or Shirley Holmes?

50:41.290 --> 50:42.030
They're not sure.

50:42.870 --> 50:44.150
In Jeff's office,

50:44.710 --> 50:47.610
I sit down on a chair near his desk.

50:48.590 --> 50:50.990
Anna is sitting in front of the desk.

50:51.790 --> 50:53.030
She looks at me quickly,

50:53.930 --> 50:56.690
then back at Jeff behind the desk.

50:58.270 --> 51:00.710
What's all this about, Jeff?

51:01.310 --> 51:02.050
She says.

51:02.770 --> 51:04.970
And why, it's Sally Hawker here.

51:06.190 --> 51:08.750
Anna, Jeff says slowly.

51:09.630 --> 51:13.050
He has Anna's laptop on his desk in front of

51:13.050 --> 51:13.250
him.

51:14.010 --> 51:16.110
He puts his hands on it.

51:17.210 --> 51:19.750
On Wednesday night this week,

51:20.130 --> 51:22.890
you downloaded a file from the office computer

51:22.890 --> 51:25.050
in the middle of the night.

51:25.750 --> 51:27.570
You used your laptop,

51:28.110 --> 51:30.430
that is my laptop,

51:30.990 --> 51:32.830
the Clayton Electric's laptop,

51:33.550 --> 51:34.490
in your home.

51:35.290 --> 51:37.710
You broke through the computer security

51:38.330 --> 51:42.690
and that's two passwords to take this file.

51:43.850 --> 51:45.910
What did you do with that file?

51:46.650 --> 51:48.190
Where is it now?

51:49.470 --> 51:50.130
Anna loves.

51:51.010 --> 51:52.530
Hey, Jeff.

51:52.530 --> 51:55.550
Jeff, what is all this?

51:56.490 --> 51:57.750
I'm your best designer.

51:58.590 --> 51:59.510
You tell me that.

52:00.230 --> 52:02.850
What file are you talking about?

52:03.690 --> 52:06.570
I didn't know anything about a file.

52:07.570 --> 52:10.610
Jeff looks at a piece of paper on his desk.

52:12.370 --> 52:16.110
I have here a screenshot of your laptop

52:16.110 --> 52:20.590
at 1.05 a.m. 24th of May.

52:20.590 --> 52:24.290
It shows the download of a file,

52:24.790 --> 52:29.590
a very important file with information about costings.

52:30.690 --> 52:32.870
What did you do with it?

52:33.450 --> 52:36.110
Who did you sell this file to?

52:37.490 --> 52:39.570
Anna isn't laughing now.

52:40.170 --> 52:41.950
She looks quickly at me,

52:42.510 --> 52:43.630
then away again.

52:44.430 --> 52:45.490
She's worried.

52:46.450 --> 52:48.110
Why am I here?

52:48.840 --> 52:50.910
Why am I not speaking?

52:52.050 --> 52:53.530
She doesn't like it.

52:54.470 --> 52:58.410
I say nothing, just sit and watch her.

52:59.630 --> 53:00.910
She looks at Jeff.

53:01.950 --> 53:03.650
Look, Jeff.

53:04.850 --> 53:05.490
She says,

53:06.310 --> 53:08.450
I don't like this.

53:09.210 --> 53:10.510
What are you saying?

53:11.450 --> 53:13.310
Are you calling me a thief?

53:14.840 --> 53:16.150
Yes, I am.

53:16.550 --> 53:18.770
Who did you sell the file to?

53:19.310 --> 53:19.870
Jeff says.

53:20.490 --> 53:24.810
Was it to someone from Spark and Flash design, maybe?

53:26.570 --> 53:27.010
What?

53:27.850 --> 53:32.230
I don't know anybody from Spark and Flash design.

53:32.970 --> 53:35.510
Who or what are they?

53:36.810 --> 53:37.790
Oh, dear.

53:38.370 --> 53:39.550
Oh, dear.

53:40.210 --> 53:41.830
Bad mistake, Anna.

53:41.830 --> 53:47.410
I take out my photographs and push them across the

53:47.410 --> 53:48.470
desk to her.

53:49.190 --> 53:51.190
Big color photos.

53:52.650 --> 53:57.450
Steven Nyberg, Director, Spark and Flash design.

53:58.410 --> 54:01.710
I say, Steve to his friends.

54:03.030 --> 54:08.290
Anna looks at the photos of her and Steven Nyberg.

54:08.290 --> 54:11.710
Her face goes white, then red.

54:12.570 --> 54:14.310
She stares at me.

54:14.990 --> 54:18.610
She wants to kill me right now.

54:19.550 --> 54:21.530
I can see it in her eyes.

54:22.510 --> 54:27.150
You are not a journalist, she says angrily.

54:28.150 --> 54:30.010
What are you, police?

54:30.870 --> 54:32.790
Or just a dirty little investigator?

54:33.350 --> 54:38.330
I hope Nyberg paid you well for all the Clayton

54:38.330 --> 54:41.770
quotations and costings, I say.

54:42.470 --> 54:44.590
Or did you do it for love?

54:45.370 --> 54:47.510
Love is cheaper for the company.

54:48.670 --> 54:51.130
Anna gets really angry now.

54:51.610 --> 54:52.770
She turns to Jeff.

54:53.530 --> 54:56.470
You think you're very clever, don't you?

54:56.930 --> 54:59.750
You and your stupid little company.

55:00.330 --> 55:02.770
You're not going to get this Blanding's company.

55:02.770 --> 55:03.230
Contract?

55:03.910 --> 55:07.090
I see B.C. don't like spending their money.

55:07.470 --> 55:09.810
They want better prices than yours.

55:10.430 --> 55:13.550
And Steve can give them those better prices.

55:15.150 --> 55:17.570
Second, bad mistake, Anna.

55:18.370 --> 55:19.590
I look quickly at Jeff.

55:20.230 --> 55:21.110
Did he hear it?

55:21.490 --> 55:23.270
Yes, he did.

55:24.270 --> 55:27.470
How do you know the client is I.C. B

55:27.470 --> 55:28.230
.C.?

55:28.230 --> 55:29.150
He says.

55:32.130 --> 55:37.010
You told us Anna's face is white again.

55:38.010 --> 55:39.650
No, I didn't.

55:40.050 --> 55:43.750
Jeff says, I said it was a Chinese bank.

55:44.170 --> 55:46.650
I didn't tell you the name of the bank.

55:47.230 --> 55:50.130
I didn't tell anybody the name of the bank.

55:50.750 --> 55:53.870
But the name I.C. B.C. was in the

55:53.870 --> 55:54.930
Blanding's quotation.

55:56.050 --> 55:58.710
So you read the file, didn't you?

55:59.150 --> 56:02.850
You broke the passwords, downloaded the file,

56:03.190 --> 56:06.690
read it, and gave it to spark and flash.

56:08.090 --> 56:09.350
You're a hacker and a thief.

56:10.290 --> 56:12.690
Do you have anything to say?

56:14.930 --> 56:16.270
Anna says nothing.

56:17.290 --> 56:19.050
There is nothing to say.

56:19.890 --> 56:22.650
She's at the end of the road and she has

56:22.650 --> 56:23.910
nowhere to go.

56:25.190 --> 56:27.070
Jeff stands up.

56:28.150 --> 56:29.970
Get out, he says.

56:31.010 --> 56:32.770
Take your things and get out.

56:33.430 --> 56:36.670
Sally, please go with her and watch her.

56:37.290 --> 56:40.310
I want her out of this building in five minutes.

56:44.230 --> 56:49.090
Chapter 7, Friday, an evening out.

56:49.890 --> 56:55.750
In the afternoon, I'm back in my office, writing emails,

56:56.350 --> 57:00.370
checking messages, doing the paperwork, the phone rings,

57:01.430 --> 57:03.090
my Sally Hawker mobile.

57:04.150 --> 57:07.170
Hey, Shirley, Jeff here.

57:07.950 --> 57:10.290
Can I come and see you?

57:11.130 --> 57:11.730
Sure.

57:12.730 --> 57:15.590
He arrives 10 minutes later.

57:16.490 --> 57:17.510
Big, happy smile.

57:18.250 --> 57:20.570
His eyes don't look worried now.

57:22.050 --> 57:25.210
Got some news, he says happily.

57:25.850 --> 57:29.270
I wanted you to be the first to know.

57:30.050 --> 57:32.650
Oh, that's nice, I say.

57:33.450 --> 57:34.990
Is it exciting news?

57:35.930 --> 57:36.590
He laughs.

57:37.870 --> 57:40.930
It is for Clayton Electric's.

57:41.290 --> 57:43.950
We've got the Blanding's house contract.

57:44.690 --> 57:45.950
I heard this afternoon.

57:46.770 --> 57:49.810
Wow, that's great news.

57:50.550 --> 57:52.470
Well done, I say.

57:53.310 --> 57:56.670
So, Spark and Flash didn't do a quotation.

57:57.770 --> 57:59.650
Or they just didn't get it?

58:00.090 --> 58:00.790
What happened?

58:01.890 --> 58:07.150
I don't know, says Jeff, but I did two quotations.

58:08.310 --> 58:11.430
I put one on the office computer on Wednesday.

58:12.230 --> 58:14.290
You know, when you told me to.

58:14.650 --> 58:19.350
But I did a second quotation with much better prices.

58:20.570 --> 58:23.730
I didn't put that on any office computer.

58:24.530 --> 58:25.990
Or send it by email.

58:27.290 --> 58:31.130
I put it on paper and sent it by motorbike

58:31.130 --> 58:31.670
messenger.

58:32.570 --> 58:36.030
Nobody in the office ever saw that quotation.

58:37.510 --> 58:38.330
I laugh.

58:40.270 --> 58:42.010
Very clever.

58:42.770 --> 58:44.590
I didn't think of that.

58:45.450 --> 58:49.130
And did ICBC like those prices then?

58:49.790 --> 58:51.090
He looks at me.

58:52.290 --> 58:56.050
You opened the file in the night and read the

58:56.050 --> 58:57.530
quotation, didn't you?

58:58.210 --> 59:00.570
You knew it was ICBC.

59:01.390 --> 59:04.630
Of course, I read it, I say.

59:05.610 --> 59:06.990
I needed to know.

59:06.990 --> 59:10.330
Oh, Jeff says.

59:11.090 --> 59:14.350
Well, Shirley Holmes, Sally Hawker.

59:14.990 --> 59:17.850
Would you like to have dinner with me tonight?

59:18.950 --> 59:21.390
A big thank you, dinner.

59:22.710 --> 59:25.670
Bread and olives at the Athena restaurant.

59:26.650 --> 59:28.510
I say, he smiles.

59:29.570 --> 59:32.330
He has a really nice smile.

59:33.470 --> 59:38.930
There's a little French restaurant near Richmond Bridge, right by

59:38.930 --> 59:39.590
the river.

59:40.110 --> 59:41.850
Very good food.

59:42.690 --> 59:45.910
They don't do bread and olives.

59:47.910 --> 59:50.910
We're meeting at seven o'clock.

59:51.370 --> 59:56.090
At home, I'm getting ready when I suddenly remember.

59:56.610 --> 59:58.150
It's Friday night.

59:59.050 --> 01:00:00.470
So he eats chicken dinner.

01:00:01.350 --> 01:00:05.750
I phone Leila, but Sahid answers the phone.

01:00:06.550 --> 01:00:10.010
He's home early because he's doing the cooking.

01:00:10.750 --> 01:00:12.970
This is going to be difficult.

01:00:14.570 --> 01:00:15.570
Sahid!

01:00:16.330 --> 01:00:21.870
I say, I'm really sorry, but I can't come tonight.

01:00:23.090 --> 01:00:24.270
I'm meeting a client.

01:00:25.690 --> 01:00:29.630
On Friday evening, Sahid says.

01:00:30.470 --> 01:00:32.110
That was last Friday.

01:00:32.710 --> 01:00:33.930
Leila told me.

01:00:34.490 --> 01:00:37.530
The client wants me to have dinner with him.

01:00:38.090 --> 01:00:39.330
To say thank you.

01:00:40.030 --> 01:00:45.130
I said, hmm, you never do that usually, Shirley.

01:00:45.930 --> 01:00:47.690
You never have dinner with clients.

01:00:48.630 --> 01:00:50.570
Clients are work, you say.

01:00:51.350 --> 01:00:54.070
Not friends to have dinner with.

01:00:54.870 --> 01:01:00.890
But this client has very beautiful brown eyes, Sahid.

01:01:01.970 --> 01:01:05.690
I just want to look into his eyes one more

01:01:05.690 --> 01:01:06.490
time.

01:01:07.690 --> 01:01:10.570
I enjoy teasing Sahid.

01:01:11.310 --> 01:01:13.370
Suddenly, he understands.

01:01:14.750 --> 01:01:17.090
Ah, okay.

01:01:17.590 --> 01:01:21.150
This client has nice brown eyes.

01:01:21.770 --> 01:01:24.430
But can he cook a chicken dinner?

01:01:26.610 --> 01:01:28.070
Of course not.

01:01:28.770 --> 01:01:33.750
I say, your chicken dinners are the best in London,

01:01:33.850 --> 01:01:34.690
Sahid.

01:01:35.290 --> 01:01:36.650
And I want some.

01:01:37.610 --> 01:01:39.490
Can you keep some for me?

01:01:40.030 --> 01:01:42.150
Can I come around on Saturday?

01:01:42.150 --> 01:01:49.190
8 o'clock, he says, and don't be late.

